And I cannot stop at the semicolon. I cannot say *the wages of sin is death* and walk away, because *that is a verdict and that is not my office.* Paul did not give that to me. Christ did not give that to me. *Judge not, that ye be not judged.* It is not mine to lift.

*A long silence. His shoulders bow lower.*

*Quieter still:*

Both halves of the verse are true. Both halves are the Word. And I cannot speak either one of them over him. Not with this mouth. Not with a mouth that took the bread from his table and said nothing.

*A breath.*

I have read the whole verse. I have read Luke sixteen. I have read what Christ said. I have nothing left to add. I have nothing left to add.

*His head drops further.*

*Then, in a voice that is barely a voice:*

Doctor Luther.

*A pause.*

Doctor Luther. I cannot do this. The verse is in the air and I cannot lift either half of it. Come. Come and say what I cannot. Come and stand where I cannot stand.

*Silence.*

*The candle on the table burns straight up. The courtyard is very still.*

